task.summary: Initial commit of Chapter 9: Parser combinators
Initial combinators for strings and chars
Initial combinators for strings and chars

Exercise 9.1
Implement monoid functions for Parser

Exercise 9.3
Many is no longer a primitive. Defined it using map2, or, and succeed.

Exercise 9.4
Implemented listOfN using map2 and succeed
Make product and map2 non-strict in their second arguments

Exercise 9.5
Added the wrap combinator for non-strictness

Exercise 9.7
Implement map2 and product with flatMap. This indicates that map2 and product are not primitives as they can be implemented with flatMap

Exercise 9.8
Implement map with flatMap. flatMap is more powerful and primitive than map

Exercise 9.9
Add combinator for parsing string until some character, 'thru' Add combinators for skipping everything before or after another parser

Exercise 9.9
Added double
Need to add combinator to attempt a parser, a token parser for keywords, root etc

Exercise 9.9
Use for-comprehensions where possible No need to explicitly show how flatMap and map are used. Any type class that defines flatMap and map can make use of the for-comprehensions

Exercise 9.9
Add end of file token, root

Add dual construct for Monoids. The dual construct arises from the fact that you have a choice between the order that you combine things in op. a1 then a2 or a2 then a1, both satisfy the monoid laws. The dual method constructs the dual of a given monoid by by flipping the 'op'.

Exercise 10.9
Had help, but used the more efficient forall method
